<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>115</anchor>   <addr>achim-jung</addr>  <route>achim-jung.xml</route>   <title>Achim Jung</title> <meta name="institution">University of Birmingham</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-9899-5637</meta><meta name="external">https://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~axj/</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>116</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-001U</addr>  <route>axt-001U.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="samson-abramsky.xml" type="local">Samson Abramsky</link></author><author><link href="achim-jung.xml" type="local">Achim Jung</link></author> </authors> <title>Basis for a dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  Let <tex>D</tex> be a dcpo and let <tex>\Downarrow (x)</tex> denote the set
  <tex>\{  y  \in  D  \mid  y  \ll  x  \}</tex>.
</p><p>  A subset <tex>B  \subseteq  D</tex> forms a basis for <tex>D</tex> if for every element <tex>x  \in   D</tex> the set <tex display="block">B_x  \vcentcolon \equiv   \Downarrow (x)  \cap  B</tex> contains a directed
  subset with supremum <tex>x</tex></p><p>  Elements of <tex>x</tex> are caled approximants to <tex>x</tex> relative to <tex>B</tex>.
</p><p>  <b>Definition 2.2.3</b> from <link href="samson-abramsky.xml" type="local" title="Abramsky">Abramsky</link> and <link href="achim-jung.xml" type="local" title="Jung">Jung</link>'s
  <link href="abramsky-jung-domain-theory-1995.xml" type="local" title="Domain Theory">Domain Theory</link>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>117</anchor>   <addr>axt-000L</addr>  <route>axt-000L.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>7</day></date> <authors><author>Samson Abramsky</author><author><link href="achim-jung.xml" type="local">Achim Jung</link></author> </authors> <title>The Stone adjunction</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  The Stone adjunction is the one formed by the <link href="axt-000M.xml" type="local" title="Open set functor">open set functor</link>  <tex>\mathcal{O}  :  \mathbf{Top}   \to   \mathbf{Frm}</tex> and the <link href="axt-000N.xml" type="local" title="Point functor">point functor</link> <tex>\mathsf{Pt}  :  \mathbf{Frm}   \to    \mathbf{Top}</tex>.
